Boxing Punch Classification

An intelligent system that automatically identifies different types of boxing punches using a small wrist-worn sensor and machine learning.

Executive Summary

This project develops an automated boxing punch classification system that can distinguish between three types of movements:

JAB
Straight punch
HOOK
Circular punch
IDLE
No punch
üí°

What does this mean? A boxer wears a small sensor on their wrist. Every time they throw a punch, the system automatically knows what type of punch it was‚Äîno human observer needed. This enables real-time training feedback and performance tracking.

How It Works

The system uses motion sensors similar to those in a smartphone or smartwatch to detect the unique movement patterns of different punches.

Sensor Captures Motion

A small sensor worn on the wrist measures two things 24 times per second:

  • Acceleration ‚Äî How fast the hand speeds up or slows down
  • Rotation ‚Äî How the wrist twists and turns

System Detects a Punch

When a punch is thrown, the sensor readings spike dramatically. The system identifies this moment by looking for the peak intensity of the movement.

Extract Key Measurements

The system captures a half-second window around each punch and calculates 108 different measurements that describe the punch's characteristics.

AI Classifies the Punch

A neural network‚Äîtrained on hundreds of labeled punches‚Äîanalyzes these measurements and determines whether it was a jab, hook, or no punch at all.

Data Collection

High-quality data is the foundation of any machine learning system. We designed a rigorous 7-day data collection protocol to ensure the model learns from diverse, real-world examples.

üîß The Sensor

We used a Holyiot-23033 Bluetooth sensor containing a BMI055 IMU (Inertial Measurement Unit). This is the same type of sensor found in fitness trackers and smartphones.

SpecificationValueWhat It Means
Sample Rate24 HzTakes 24 measurements per second
Axes6Measures 3 directions of acceleration + 3 directions of rotation
CommunicationBluetoothWirelessly sends data to a computer

üìç Sensor Placement

The sensor is worn on the left wrist (the lead hand in orthodox boxing stance). This hand throws jabs and lead hooks‚Äîthe punches we want to classify.

  • Position: Back of wrist, 2cm from wrist bone toward elbow
  • Attachment: Tight strap so sensor moves with the wrist, not independently

Collection Schedule

Data was collected over 7 days with specific goals each day:

DayFocusPurpose
Day 1BaselineCalibrate the sensor and establish baseline readings
Day 2Jabs OnlyCollect pure jab examples at various speeds and intensities
Day 3Hooks OnlyCollect pure hook examples at various speeds and intensities
Day 4MixedRandomized jabs and hooks to simulate real training
Day 5ValidationHold-out data for unbiased testing
Day 6Stress TestEdge cases, fatigue, and "trick" movements
Day 7Final TestCompletely blind evaluation

Figure 1: Data Distribution by Day

The left chart shows the number of sensor readings per day. The right chart shows the number of individual punches recorded. Days 2 and 3 have the most data because they focused on collecting many examples of jabs and hooks.

Variation in Training Data

To make the model robust, we varied the punches in multiple ways:

Intensity
Light, Medium, Power
Speed
Slow, Medium, Fast
Context
Standing, Moving

Figure 2: Raw Sensor Data from a Jab Training Session

This shows what the sensor "sees" during training. The top two panels show acceleration and rotation readings. The vertical dashed lines mark when a beep sounded (signaling the boxer to throw a punch). Notice the clear spikes in activity right after each beep‚Äîthose are the punches.

Labeling Methodology

For the AI to learn, every punch needs a correct label. We developed a precise beep-based system to ensure accurate labeling without manual review of every punch.

üéØ

The Challenge: With hundreds of punches to label, manually watching video and tagging each one would be extremely time-consuming and error-prone. Our solution uses audio cues and automated peak detection.

The Beep System

Each punch is triggered by an audio beep. The boxer hears the beep and throws the punch. Since we control when the beep happens and what type of punch is requested, we know exactly what to expect.

[BEEP sounds]  ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚ñ∫  [Boxer throws punch]  ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚ñ∫  [Returns to guard]
      ‚îÇ                        ‚îÇ                              ‚îÇ
   t = 0 ms              t = 50-300 ms                  t = 500+ ms
                               ‚îÇ
                         ‚îå‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚î¥‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îê

How Labels Are Assigned

Single-Type Sessions (Days 2-3)

When a session contains only jabs or only hooks, every punch in that session gets the same label automatically.

Example: During "Session 5: Power Jabs," every punch detected is labeled as "jab."

Mixed Sessions (Days 4-6)

A voice announcement precedes each beep, telling the boxer what to throw:

  1. System announces "JAB" or "HOOK"
  2. Beep sounds 1 second later
  3. Boxer throws the announced punch
  4. System labels the detected punch accordingly

Finding the Punch Peak

The exact moment of a punch is identified by finding the peak rotation speed (when the wrist is moving fastest). This is more reliable than acceleration because rotation clearly distinguishes punching from other movements.

Rotation Magnitude = ‚àö(gyro_x¬≤ + gyro_y¬≤ + gyro_z¬≤)
Combines all three rotation directions into a single "intensity" value

Figure 3: Peak Detection by Punch Type

Each panel shows the rotation magnitude over time for a jab, hook, and idle period. The red vertical line marks the detected peak. Notice how jabs and hooks have sharp peaks while idle periods remain flat‚Äîthis is how the system knows a punch occurred.

Extracting the Analysis Window

Once we find the peak, we extract a 500-millisecond window centered around it:

        ‚îÇ‚óÑ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ 150 ms ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÇ‚óÑ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ 350 ms ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÇ
        ‚îÇ     BEFORE        ‚îÇ       AFTER         ‚îÇ
        ‚îÇ   (wind-up)       ‚îÇ   (follow-through)  ‚îÇ
        ‚îÇ                   ‚îÇ                     ‚îÇ
   ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îº‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ*‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îº‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ
                          PEAK
        ‚îÇ‚óÑ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ 500 ms total ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚ñ∫‚îÇ

Why This Window?

  • 150 ms before: Captures any "telegraphing" (early movement that gives away the punch)
  • 350 ms after: Captures the follow-through and hand retraction
  • ~12 data points: At 24 Hz, this gives us about 12 sensor readings to analyze

Feature Extraction

Raw sensor data needs to be converted into meaningful measurements the AI can understand. We extract 108 features from each punch window.

üìä

What are features? Features are numerical descriptions of the data. Instead of showing the AI a raw stream of numbers, we calculate statistics like "average acceleration" or "peak rotation speed" that capture the essence of each punch.

Feature Categories

Time-Domain Features (60 total)

Basic statistics calculated for each of the 6 sensor channels:

FeatureWhat It Measures
MeanAverage value during the punch
Standard DeviationHow much the values vary
Min / MaxLowest and highest values
RangeDifference between max and min
SkewnessWhether values are lopsided high or low
KurtosisWhether there are extreme spikes

6 sensor channels √ó 10 statistics = 60 features

Frequency-Domain Features (30 total)

Analyzes the "rhythm" of the movement using Fourier Transform:

FeatureWhat It Measures
FFT MeanAverage frequency content
FFT MaxDominant frequency strength
FFT EnergyTotal "power" in the movement
Dominant FrequencyThe main rhythm of the punch

6 sensor channels √ó 5 frequency features = 30 features

Magnitude Features (12 total)

Overall intensity regardless of direction:

Acceleration Magnitude = ‚àö(accel_x¬≤ + accel_y¬≤ + accel_z¬≤)

2 magnitude types √ó 6 statistics = 12 features

Cross-Axis Correlations (6 total)

How different directions move together (helps distinguish straight punches from rotational ones):

  • Correlation between X and Y acceleration
  • Correlation between X and Z acceleration
  • ... and so on for all axis pairs
108
Total Features Per Punch

The Classification Model

We use a Multi-Layer Perceptron (MLP)‚Äîa type of neural network‚Äîto classify punches based on the 108 extracted features.

üß†

What is a neural network? It's a computer program inspired by how the brain works. It learns patterns from examples. Show it hundreds of labeled punches, and it learns to recognize what makes a jab different from a hook.

Network Architecture

The neural network has 4 layers that progressively distill the 108 input features into a final classification:

Training Process

The model learns by seeing many examples and adjusting itself to minimize mistakes:

ParameterValueExplanation
Training Samples530Total punches the model learned from
Iterations27Times the model went through the data
Early StoppingYesStops when performance stops improving (prevents overfitting)
Final Loss0.054How wrong the model is (lower is better)

Figure 4: Training Loss Curve

This shows how the model improved during training. The "loss" (error) drops quickly in the first few iterations and then levels off. The model stopped automatically after 27 iterations when it detected no further improvement.

The "idle" class has fewer samples than jabs and hooks. This explains why the model performs less well on idle detection‚Äîit simply had fewer examples to learn from.

Model Results

The model was tested on Session 19‚Äîdata it had never seen during training. This "blind test" shows how well the system performs in real-world conditions.

Figure 5: Test Session Sensor Data (Session 19)

The complete sensor trace from the blind test session. This session contained 10 jabs and 10 hooks in randomized order‚Äîthe model had to classify each one without knowing the correct answer.

Side-by-side comparison of a jab and hook from the test session. Notice the different patterns: jabs show more linear acceleration, while hooks show more rotational movement.

Classification Results

87%
Overall Accuracy (20 of 23 correct)

Figure 8: Confusion Matrix

This shows what the model predicted vs. what was actually thrown. Diagonal cells (dark blue) are correct predictions. Off-diagonal cells are mistakes. The model correctly identified 9/10 jabs and 10/10 hooks.

Per-Class Performance

Punch TypePrecisionRecallF1 ScoreSamples
JAB 90% 90% 0.90 10
HOOK 91% 100% 0.95 10
IDLE 50% 33% 0.40 3
üìà

Understanding the metrics:

  • Precision: When the model says "jab," how often is it actually a jab?
  • Recall: Of all actual jabs, how many did the model catch?
  • F1 Score: A balanced combination of precision and recall (1.0 is perfect)

‚úì Key Findings

  • Hooks: Perfect detection (100% recall)‚Äîthe model never misses a hook
  • Jabs: Excellent detection (90% recall)‚Äîonly 1 jab was misclassified
  • Idle: Needs improvement (33% recall)‚Äîmore training data needed

Biomechanical Analysis

Beyond classification, the system provides detailed performance metrics for each correctly identified punch, enabling objective technique assessment.

Metrics Computed

MetricWhat It MeasuresWhy It Matters
Peak G-Force Maximum acceleration (in multiples of gravity) Indicates punch power
Peak Velocity Estimated hand speed (m/s) Faster punches are harder to defend
Telegraphing Movement before the punch Reveals if opponent can see it coming
Retraction Time How fast the hand returns to guard Slow retraction leaves you vulnerable
Snap Quality Timing of wrist rotation vs. arm extension Good "snap" increases impact
Guard Consistency Stillness before punching Stable guard prevents telegraphing

Each bar represents one correctly classified punch. Blue = jab, Red = hook, Gray = idle. The charts show G-force, velocity, rotation rate, and guard consistency for each punch.

AI Boxing Coach Analysis

The biomechanical data was analyzed by an AI boxing coach (powered by Google Gemini) to provide actionable training recommendations.

ü§ñ AI Coach Performance Report

C+

Overall Grade

Good power, technique needs refinement

Physical output (velocity and g-force) is impressive for a lead hand. However, technique is currently a "glass cannon"‚Äîpunches are fast but predictable. The jab is telegraphed 89% of the time, meaning a skilled opponent will see every lead coming.

üí™ Jab Analysis

Strengths: Excellent speed (15.36 m/s average), very high snap quality (8/9 rated "Good"), fast retraction (4ms).

Weakness: Critical telegraphing rate (89%). The boxer is likely dropping their hand slightly or "cocking" their shoulder before the jab fires.

Recommendation: Focus on the "frozen shoulder" jab‚Äîthe punch should travel from chin to target in a straight line with zero precursor movement.

ü•ä Hook Analysis

Strengths: Most powerful punch (3.04 G average), low telegraphing (only 20%), higher velocity than jabs.

Weakness: 50% of hooks rated "Poor" snap quality. Retraction time (194ms) is dangerously slow‚Äînearly 50x slower than the jab. The boxer is "lingering" on the target.

Recommendation: Think of the hook like a whip, not a club. Impact and snap back to the jaw immediately.

üéØ Top 3 Recommended Drills

  1. The "Wall Jab": Stand with left shoulder against a wall. Throw jabs. If elbow hits the wall first, you're telegraphing.
  2. The "Elastic Hook" Drill: Use a light resistance band. Focus on the return of the hook‚Äîmake the return faster than the punch itself.
  3. Double-Jab, Reset: Throw a double jab, ensuring the lead hand touches your temple between the first and second punch.

‚ú® Positive Highlights

  • Lead Hand Velocity: Natural hand speed is high‚Äîreaching 19.5 m/s on the best hook.
  • Jab Snap: Despite telegraphing, when the jab lands, it lands correctly with excellent "pop."
  • Hook Stealth: Only 20% telegraphing on hooks‚Äîcan use this to set up combinations.
"You've got the speed and the power, but right now you're shouting your intentions to your opponent. Tighten up the 'leakage' in your jab and snap that hook back like it touched a hot stove. Keep working!"
‚Äî AI Boxing Coach

Conclusions & Next Steps

‚úì What We Achieved

  • Built a working punch classification system with 87% accuracy
  • Perfect hook detection (100%) and excellent jab detection (90%)
  • Developed objective biomechanical metrics for technique assessment
  • Integrated AI coaching for actionable training feedback

‚ö†Ô∏è Limitations & Improvements

  • Idle detection: Needs more training data (only 33% recall)
  • Single user: Model trained on one boxer‚Äîmay need retraining for others
  • Left hand only: Currently only classifies lead hand punches
  • Sample rate: 24 Hz may miss some fast movements‚Äîhigher rate could improve accuracy

üöÄ Future Development

  • Collect data from multiple boxers to create a universal model
  • Add right hand sensor for complete punch tracking
  • Develop real-time mobile app for live training feedback
  • Expand to more punch types (uppercuts, body shots, combinations)
